  "response_text": "**Understanding the Difference between Speed and Velocity**\n\nSpeed and velocity are two fundamental concepts in physics that are often confused with each other due to their similarities. However, they have distinct meanings and implications.\n\n### Speed\n\nSpeed is a scalar quantity that represents the rate of change of an object's position with respect to time. It is a measure of how fast an object is moving, without considering the direction of the motion. In other words, speed is a measure of how quickly an object covers a certain distance.\n\n### Velocity\n\nVelocity, on the other hand, is a vector quantity that represents the rate of change of an object's position with respect to time, including its direction. It is a measure of both the speed of an object and its direction of motion.\n\n### Key Differences\n\n|  | Speed | Velocity |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Definition** | Rate of change of position with respect to time (scalar) | Rate of change of position with respect to time, including direction",
